The ANC is calling for unity in the wake of the outcome of the party&#8217;s National Working Committee meeting, where the party backed President Jacob Zuma. JOHANNESBURG - The African National Congress (ANC) is calling for unity in the wake of the outcome of the party s National Working Committee (NWC) meeting, where the party backed President Jacob Zuma saying as disagreements will emerge an atmosphere for genuine debate and criticism must be created. The party held a media briefing at Luthuli House earlier on Wednesday following the NWC meeting. NWC emphasises the need for unity of the ANC and the alliance. A call for ANC members to close ranks in the interests of the country, secretary General Gwede Mantashe says that doesn't mean there must not be disagreement. While disagreements remain, as they always will in the execution of our revolution an atmosphere for genuine debate, criticism and self-criticism must always be created. The party says it s reflected on calls from alliance partners the South African Communist Party (SACP) and Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu) for the president to step down, saying they will meet with them to hear them out.(Edited by Zamangwane Shange)